//206. Reverse Linked List
//Given the head of a singly linked list, reverse the list, and return the reversed list.
//Example 1:
//Input: head = [1,2,3,4,5]
//Output: [5,4,3,2,1]
//Example 2:
//Input: head = [1,2]
//Output: [2,1]
//Example 3:
//Input: head = []
//Output: []


Brute Force Approach -> (Using Extra Array)

class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* reverseList(ListNode* head) {
        vector<int> values;
        ListNode* curr = head;
        while(curr) {                                // Same as while(curr != nullptr) {
            values.push_back(curr->val);
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        curr = head;
        for(int i = values.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            curr->val = values[i];
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        return head;
    }
};

Intuition ->
Store all node values in an array.
Traverse the linked list again and overwrite each node with values from the array in reverse order.
The linked list structure remains unchanged, only the values are reversed.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes
Reason:
We traverse the linked list twice.

Space Complexity -> O(n)
Reason:
An additional array stores all node values.

Optimal Approach -> (Iterative Pointer Reversal)

class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* reverseList(ListNode* head) {
       ListNode* prev = nullptr;
        ListNode* curr = head;
        while(curr) {
            ListNode* nextNode = curr->next;
            curr->next = prev;
            prev = curr;
            curr = nextNode;
        }
        return prev;
    }
};

Intuition ->

For every node:
Store next node
Reverse current node's pointer
Move prev forward
Move curr forward
Gradually the entire linked list gets reversed.
At the end:
prev
points to the new head.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes
Reason:
Every node is visited exactly once.

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Reason:
Only a few pointer variables are used.

